Malicious URL Detection

This project uses machine learning to classify URLs as benign or malicious. Raw URL data is loaded from a CSV, cleaned and featurized, then split into train/test sets. Multiple classifiers (SVM, k-NN, Random Forest) are trained on the same features and evaluated with standard metrics and visualizations.

Dataset (Kaggle)
-----------------
The pipeline expects the input file at data/urldata.csv (columns: number, url, label, result; labels: benign / malicious). This file is not included in the repo.

- Get the dataset from Kaggle: Search for "Malicious URL" or "URL classification" datasets on Kaggle(https://www.kaggle.com/datasets). Download the CSV and place it as data/urldata.csv (create the data/ folder if needed).
- After adding the file, run data_processing.ipynb to generate the train/test CSVs in code/outputs/.


Project Description

The pipeline has two main stages: (1) data_processing.ipynb prepares the dataset and produces train/test CSV files; (2) each model notebook (SVM, k-NN, Random Forest) loads those files, trains a classifier, and reports metrics and plots.


data_processing.ipynb

- Input: ../data/urldata.csv (columns: number, url, label, result).
- Cleaning & labels: Converts labels to binary (0 = benign, 1 = malicious), drops empty/duplicate URLs, and standardizes URLs (lowercase, optional http:// prefix, normalized scheme/netloc/path/query).
- Feature extraction: Builds 13 numeric features from each URL, including: url_length, host_length, path_length, query_length, count_digits, count_specials, count_upper, count_subdomains, digit_ratio, symbol_ratio, uppercase_ratio, entropy, and is_https.
- Train/test split: Uses an 80/20 stratified split, then applies StandardScaler to the numeric features (fit on train only).
- Output: Writes outputs/X_train.csv, outputs/X_test.csv, outputs/y_train.csv, and outputs/y_test.csv for use by the model notebooks.


SVM.ipynb

- Input: The CSV files produced by data_processing (X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test).
- Model: LinearSVC with class_weight="balanced". Hyperparameters are tuned via GridSearchCV with 3-fold StratifiedKFold over C, loss (hinge, squared_hinge), tol, and max_iter; scoring is macro F1.
- Evaluation: Reports accuracy, precision, recall, F1, macro F1, ROC-AUC, and PR-AUC; prints a classification report and confusion matrix.
- Visuals: ROC curve, Precision–Recall curve, and confusion matrix heatmap. Optionally saves the best model with joblib.


Environment Setup

- Python
- Required Libraries
     numpy
     pandas
     scikit-learn
     matplotlib
     jupyter


Files

- data_processing.ipynb
- SVM.ipynb


Run Instructions

- Run data_processing.ipynb to obtain X_test, X_train, y_test, and y_train CSV files in code/outputs/.
- Run each of the model notebooks (SVM, k-NN, Random Forest).
- Each model uses the same X and y CSV files and presents outcomes in metric tables and visuals.